Some crosstalk simulations

Unless otherwise indicated, the following simulations were performed with the "large" feed that has a flat ~50-60% efficiency across the band.
This feed sticks out exactly 218 mm (this is the position at which it reaches that good efficiency).

Crosstalks within the feed alone

To start with, I simulated the crosstalks within the feed when it is not installed on a dish. These simulations were performed with, and without balun:
  1. Without balun: the port is across the narrow bottom of the slot (this simulation is faster, but not realistic),
  2. With balun: a stripline goes across the narrow bottom of the slot, shorted on one end, and the port is at the other end.
Here is a representation of the balun setup:

Here are the results:

It is obvious from these simulations that without baluns, the S2,1 cannot be properly simulated: the -170 dB range is effectively zero. However, when simulating the full 2-dish setup, adding the balun will make the simulations significantly longer.

Crosstalks in the full 2-dish system, with and without baluns

First, here is a visual representation of the setup of the polarizations and corresponding port numbers:

Let's look at the crosstalk for the most basic setup:

  • 6 m dish,
  • Focal ratio = 0.25 (focus is at the exact same height as the rim),
  • Feed sticks out 218 mm (this is the position of its phase center),
  • Dish distance (rim-to-rim) is 40 cm.
Let's also simulate with, and without balun.

Here are the results (note that you can turn curves on and off by clicking on their color in the legend):

Breaking down the results:

  • S2,1
    • Without baluns: -120 dB, which is close to the feed-only S2,1 (-170 dB presented above), plus the expected contribution from the S3,1 (-50 dB).
      • With baluns: Very similar to the feed-only S2,1 with balun.
  • S3,1 and S4,2: the results are the same with or without balun.
  • S4,1: the balun adds >~-20 dB, which makes sense as we've seen that the balun picks up the perpendicular polarization in the S2,1 sims.
Theses results indicate that it makes sense to use feed-only simulations to check for the S2,1's, and no-balun simulations to check for the S3,1's, S4,2's, and S4,1's. This will save a lot of time.

Increasing the dish distance

The simulations above were performed with 40 cm dish distance. Let's look at what different dish distances might produce.

Note that I will only present the S3,1's. Since I worry about the dish-to-dish crosstalk, I will not use baluns, and so I will not present S2,1's. I will also not show the S4,2's since they are significiantly lower than the S3,1's and there is no reason why increasing the dish distance would increase the S4,2's. For these reasons, I also don't present the S4,1's.

Increasing the dish distance does not make a large difference.

Adding a fence

The second idea is to add a fence around the rim of the dish:

I simulated different fence heights, here they are, for a constant 40 cm distance:

The fence does decrease the crosstalks, but it has to be large (>50 cm) to beat down the crosstalks by 10 dB.

Making the dishes deeper

Another way of mitigating the crosstalks is to make the dishes deeper, i.e. the focus would now be below the rim of the dish. I simulated two different ways of doing that: fixing the position of the focus and extending the diameter, or fixing the diameter and lowering the focus.

Fixing the position of the focus

For a 6 m dish with an f/D=0.25, the focus is 1.5 m from the bottom, which is also the "depth" (=height of the rim) of the dish. We can make the dish deeper by fixing the focus at 1.5 m, but extending the diameter so that the dish gets deeper. I chose the "extra depth" to be the independent variable, and I simulated 10, 20, 40, and 80 cm extra depths. Here are the corresponding dish properties:

Extra depth (mm) Total depth (mm) Corresponding diameter (mm) Corresponding focal ratio
0 1500 6000 0.25
100 1600 6197 0.242
200 1700 6387 0.235
400 1900 6753 0.222
800 2300 7430 0.202

Here are the results, for a constant 40 cm dish distance:

Hence we see that larger, deeper dishes reduce crosstalk by a significant amount, but the dishes are significantly larger, too.

Simulations at 45 degrees

Since the S4,2 crosstalk is roughly 20 dB lower than the S3,1, this suggests that the angle between a polarization plane and the dish translation vector is a significant variable. I simulated the following setup:

Note that in this setup, the feed legs need to be rotate 45 degrees too, which may not be desirable from a mechanical standpoint.

In this case, thanks to symmetry, I really only need to excite one port. Here are the results, for a fixed 40 cm dish distance, compared to the non-rotated (0 deg) case:

Things to notice:

  1. The S3,1 45 deg (equivalent to S4,2 in the 45 degrees case, which I didn't simulate) is lower than the S3,1 of the 0 degrees case by about 10 dB in the low frequency range, but is 10 dB higher than the S4,2 of the 0 degrees case,
  2. The S4,1 45 deg is as large as the S3,1,
  3. The 45 degree cross-dish crosstalks have a bump around 1 GHz.
